# .rules — `agent` (OSS)

> **Single source of truth for this repo — read this first.** Humans and AI assistants (Claude,
> Gemini, Codex, …) follow it; `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, and `GEMINI.md` all point here. Keep it
> **concise and current**: the *plan* lives in [`ROADMAP.md`](./ROADMAP.md), the *why* in the
> [ADRs](./docs/adr/), the *how-to* in [`CONTRIBUTING.md`](./CONTRIBUTING.md). Don't duplicate them here.

## What this repo is
The **open-source, Apache-2.0** eBPF node agent that observes and secures Kubernetes workloads,
purpose-built to understand **GPU/AI inference** workloads. Open-core pair with the private
`agent-cloud` control plane. Ships as a single-binary **DaemonSet**.

## Commands
| Task | Command |
|------|---------|
| Build (cross-compiles + embeds the eBPF object) | `cargo xtask build` |
| Run the agent (loads eBPF — needs root) | `cargo xtask run -- --once` |
| Test (host, no privilege) | `cargo test` |
| Lint — must be clean | `cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings` and `cargo fmt --all --check` |
| Supply chain | `cargo deny check` |
| Regenerate kernel bindings | `cargo xtask codegen` (needs `bpftool` + `aya-tool`) |

- **Do NOT `cargo build --workspace` / `--all`.** The `ebpf` crate is excluded from `default-members`
  and only builds for the BPF target (via `build.rs`/`xtask`) — a host build of it fails. Use a bare
  `cargo build` / `cargo clippy` (default-members) or `-p <crate>`.
- Loading eBPF needs `CAP_BPF`/`CAP_PERFMON`; `xtask run` uses `sudo`. Full setup + the test tiers:
  [`CONTRIBUTING.md`](./CONTRIBUTING.md).

## Stack & layout
- **Rust**; eBPF via **`aya`** (pure Rust — **NOT** Wasmtime, an abandoned idea); k8s via `kube-rs`.
  Cargo workspace, scaffolded from `aya-template`.
- Model after: `bpfman/bpfman` (Rust+aya+k8s — closest match), `cilium/tetragon`, `falcosecurity/falco`.
```
crates/common    #[repr(C)] event types — the kernel ⇄ userspace ⇄ cloud contract (no_std). The spine.
crates/ebpf      eBPF programs (no_std, BPF target): tracepoints/kprobes/LSM
crates/agent     userspace binary: load eBPF, drain ring buffer, enrich, alert, export
crates/enrich    k8s enrichment via kube-rs (cgroup → container → pod)   [M2, not yet]
crates/rules     detection engine                                        [M5, not yet]
crates/exporter  gRPC/proto export to agent-cloud                        [M7, not yet]
xtask            build orchestration (dev-only, never shipped)
```

## Invariants — do not trade these away
The *rule* is here; the *why* is in the linked ADR.
- **One-way dependency: cloud → OSS.** This repo **NEVER** imports `agent-cloud`; the agent stays
  fully usable self-hosted with zero cloud. ([ADR-0007](./docs/adr/0007-open-core-one-way-dependency.md))
- **`common` is the contract.** `#[repr(C)]` events (kernel⇄userspace) + proto (userspace⇄cloud);
  `no_std`, dependency-light; evolve **additively only** — never reorder/resize existing fields.
  ([ADR-0005](./docs/adr/0005-event-abi-two-encodings.md))
- **The verifier is the gate** — correctness before performance; a program that doesn't load doesn't
  ship. ([ADR-0001](./docs/adr/0001-ring-buffer-over-perf-buffer.md))
- **Never hand-roll kernel structs** — read them via CO-RE; bindings come from `cargo xtask codegen`.
  ([ADR-0002](./docs/adr/0002-co-re-btf-over-compile-per-kernel.md))
- **Capture is never gated on enrichment** (cold-start): attach probes first, seed from `/proc`, emit
  `Unknown` rather than drop, never block the ring-buffer drain.
  ([ADR-0006](./docs/adr/0006-cold-start-and-resync-contract.md))
- **One self-contained binary, no sidecars.** ([ADR-0004](./docs/adr/0004-single-self-contained-binary.md))
- **Every feature points at AI/GPU workloads** — the wedge, not generic k8s observability.

## Code conventions
- `cargo fmt` + `cargo clippy` clean. **No `unwrap`/`expect`/`panic!` outside tests** (workspace
  `deny` lints; `clippy.toml` re-allows them in tests). eBPF crate is `no_std`; userspace is stable.
- **Toolchain split:** the root pins **stable**; `crates/ebpf` pins **nightly** (its own
  `rust-toolchain.toml`) for the BPF target, and `build.rs` bridges them — don't "simplify" it away.
  ([ADR-0003](./docs/adr/0003-stable-root-nightly-ebpf-toolchain-split.md))
- **eBPF event hygiene:** zero the reserved ring-buffer slot, then write fields in place — never build
  on the stack and copy (the verifier rejects uninitialized/padding bytes). Keep `#[repr(C)]` types
  padding-free (u64s first) and `const`-assert the size.
- **Capture identity in-kernel, at event time** (`cgroup_id`, `mnt_ns_inum`, `bpf_ktime_get_ns`) — the
  only moment it's guaranteed to exist; userspace post-resolution is racy.
- **Ring-buffer size** must be a power of two **and** a page multiple (else `bpf_map_create` → `-EINVAL`).
- **Boot preflight:** check BTF, cgroup v2, kernel ≥ 5.8, and `/sys/kernel/security/lsm`; if `bpf` is
  absent, `WARN` and degrade enforcement to `bpf_send_signal` + `cgroup/connect`.
- The cgroup crawler scans only `kubepods.slice` and `statx`es **directories only**, on a low-priority
  task — never leaf files (`cpu.pressure`/`memory.stat`), or a dense node spikes the agent's own CPU.

## Repo etiquette
- Commits: one logical change each, imperative subject. **Never add AI co-author / attribution
  trailers.** Never commit secrets or fetched/generated data.
- Work in milestones (`M0`…`M7`); open each with its **ADR** ([`docs/adr/`](./docs/adr/)), close it
  with a tag + a working demo + green CI. Write a new ADR for any significant, hard-to-reverse call.

